"v. 闪烁，闪耀；n. 灿烂的光华；诱惑力，魅力 【英】 v.闪烁,闪耀(shine brightly);n.灿烂的光华(sparkl ing light);诱惑力,魅力(attract iveness) v. 闪烁, 闪耀 = glisten = flash; n 光彩诱人; 华而不实; 闪烁的光辉 【记】 = glisten 【记】gl- 看 + lit (light的过去时) 能看的闪光的 glitter (v.)  c.1300, glideren (late 14c. as gliteren), from a Scandinavian source such as Old Norse glitra ""to glitter,"" from glit ""brightness,"" from Proto-Germanic *glit- ""shining, bright"" (cognates: Old English glitenian ""to glitter, shine; be distinguished,"" Old High German glizzan, German glitzern, Gothic glitmunjan), from PIE *ghleid- (cognates: Greek khlidon, khlidos ""ornament""), from root *ghel- (2) ""to shine,"" with derivatives referring to bright materials and gold (see glass). Related: Glittered; glittering. The noun is c.1600, from the verb. Glitter rock is from 1972."
